	<li>about the most important factors to work out in a group or with a buddy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><strong>An African proverb says</strong></em></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><strong>“If you want to go fast, go alone. If you want to go far, go together.”</strong></em></p>\r\nBeing fast is good and a lot of fun, however working out alone is not for everybody. Circumstances in your life make you to go alone for a while but the long-term efficient way is always a team effort. Going alone is great to cover a lot of ground, especially if you don’t want to rely on others, but it also gets you weary and worn. Depending on your goals and discipline, there’s a place for both. Sometimes you need to pull ahead and move fast. Other times you need a great team to carry you and work with you on subtle things that provide the last spark to elevate you to the next level.\r\n\r\nAdvanced and progressive bodyweight training needs a lot of attention especially in the beginning. Although the concepts are not difficult to learn let more advanced athletes help and guide you. For this reason we recommend to work out with a trainer, a group or a workout buddy especially in the beginning. Afterwards it is your schedule, time preference and social factor to either work out with others or go the path alone for a while.\r\n\r\n<strong>A huge reason to go alone is related to time, your preferences but also your fitness level.</strong>\r\n\r\nThere are people out there that just can\'t find enough extra time to travel to and from a gym three or four times a week. Adding an hour for gym travel time is inconvenient and inefficient for some. One of the biggest advantages of training alone is that you can exercise at your own pace and decide when, how much, and what you will do. If you are this type of person you will consider crowded gyms as plain awful. Packed gyms cannot only be a major distraction but also hugely demotivating for oneself.\r\n\r\n<strong>If these points haven’t convinced you or you are in general a person that needs the extra spark to be motivated, maybe working out with another person is for you.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe number-one negative why people quit their training is the lack of motivation. You need a different sort of mind-set to be consistent about training alone. You always have dozens of things to do around a house, and it\'s very easy to let them get in the way of training. Luckily progressive bodyweight training is motivation in itself because you learn something new each session. The learning factor is also the number one reason you should consider training with others. A workout buddy can help you spot flaws in your form and technique, a trainer can give you tips to reach the next level and a workout group can give you a new challenge from time to time and be a lot of fun. Let them help you to achieve your fitness goals and enjoy the sessions. Go with a group of dedicated buddies if you want to be constantly motivated and supported. If you are more up for a competition and strive more under those circumstances, consider working out with others.\r\n\r\nJust think about what type of person you are and use each option smartly. Understand alone workouts and with others as a tactical tool to reach your goals faster. Enjoy!\r\n\r\nWe are sure we missed a couple of good other reasons. Leave us a comment and let’s talk about this. Which type of training person are you?\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Ykings is progressive bodyweight training. Learn elite skills like muscleups, handstand pushups or the human flag among other epic moves step by step. Subscribe to the coach for personalized workout weeks and raid the skills you want to learn with specific skill training. Exercise alone in the shadows, reach out to the community in the app, ask a featured athlete and join us via <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/official.ykings/\">Facebook</a> in one of our many public workout sessions.</em></strong>\r\n\r\n