16-07-07 10:48:03','2016-07-07 10:48:03','<strong>Form and technique - shoulders 1on1</strong>\r\n\r\nWhoever is starting out to hunt down advanced bodyweight skills will come across very important terminology that we also use in our video tutorials and blog posts. Following, we are covering the most important terms.\r\n\r\n<strong>Protraction and retraction</strong>\r\nProtraction and retraction (or abduction and adduction, respectively) are opposites. In protraction, the scapulae (aka shoulder blades) move forward and outwards from each other, while in retraction, the scapulae move backwards and towards each other.\r\n\r\nPlease see pictures below.\r\n\r\nPicture 1 Protraction              Picture 2 Retraction\r\n\r\nYou protract by pushing your shoulders forward, trying to touch them in front of your chest as you can see in a perfect pushup position.\r\n\r\nYou retract by squeezing the shoulderblades together as you can see here in a perfect deadhang on the bar.\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Protraction is mainly important during planche work, while retracting is important in rows and other forms of horizontal pulling.</em></strong>\r\n\r\nTo isolate your joints and to be less injury prone there is two other shoulder positions for certain exercises you have to learn about.\r\n\r\n<strong>Depression and elevation</strong>\r\nDepressing the scapulae means you\'re moving them down towards your butt, like in a support hold. Elevation is the opposite, where the shoulder blades move up towards your head.\r\n\r\nPicture 1 Depression          Picture 2 Elevation\r\n\r\nYou depress by pushing your shoulders down, trying to get your arms as low as they can go like here in the L-Sit.\r\n\r\nYou elevate by pushing your shoulders up, as if you\'re trying to cover your ears as you can see here with a handstand.\r\n\r\n<strong>Depression is important during dipping, support holds, and L-sits. It\'s also important to do during horizontal pulling and pushing (to prevent shrugging up). Elevation is mainly important during handstand-related exercises.</strong>','Shoulder positioning demystified','','inherit','closed','closed','','1686-revision-v1','','','2016-07-07 10:48:03','2016-07-07 10:48:03','',1686,'http://ykings.com/index.php/2016/07/07/1686-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1689,1,'2016-07-07 15:29:43','2016-07-07 15:29:43','After reading this article you will know\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>why it makes sense to know about strength types</li>\r\n 	<li>how to measure and compare strength</li>\r\n 	<li>how you can align your training to strength</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nStrength can be split into several different forms, and to address the right type in accordance with your goals is what we are going to cover in this blog post. What you will do in strength training heavily depends on what kind of strength suits your needs.\r\n\r\nWe all have our own preferences and goals, and none of the strength types described here is superior to the others. Generally we recommend prioritizing a specific strength type for a certain period of time. Grow through adversity and explore other worlds from time to time. To be clear, working on one does not mean you are excluding the others, just know which strength type you want to emphasize more than the others to make the most efficient progress towards the goals you have.\r\n\r\nSo what are these strength types, what do they mean and how do you integrate them in your training?\r\n\r\nWe cover four basic types of strength\r\n\r\n★ Absolute Strength\r\n\r\n★ Relative Strength\r\n\r\n★ Power (aka Explosive or Speed Strength)\r\n\r\n★ Strength Endurance\r\n\r\n<strong>Absolute Strength </strong>\r\n\r\nAbsolute Strength is the maximum force your musculature can exert for a particular action, whether it’s a press, a squat, or a pull.\r\n\r\nThe most renowned sport for absolute strength is powerlifting. Everything powerlifters do is geared towards improving a single rep Max in three lifts -- the squat, bench press, and deadlift. In general, training for this strength type involves lifting weights at 85%+ of the maximal weight you can lift for several sets of a few repetitions. So in that discipline and strength type there is a particular way to measure it. It is total weight lifted.\r\n\r\nCan you measure and compare every sport with this method? How about calisthenics? Calisthenics strength competitions can’t be measure that way, because don’t forget that participants need to carry their own weight as well. Here you will need either weight classes or consider the pound for pound type of strength which is what we will cover next.\r\n\r\n<strong>Relative Strength </strong>\r\n\r\nRelative strength concerns your maximum effort in relation to your bodyweight. I am pretty sure you heard the term pound for pound before, either from boxing or recent UFC discussions lingering around Jon Jones (Light Heavyweight) and Demetrius Johnson (Featherweight). Both fighters are the top of their class in their respective weight class. People love to compare the best of the best to find out who is the greatest of them all. One way to do it is with “pound for pound” strength. This strength type is very suitable to explain the strength in connection to the respective bodyweight and therefore considers but also favours people who are of lower bodyweight.\r\n\r\nSeems like relative strength is the appropriate way to compare also athletes of advanced bodyweight training. Gymnasts and for this matter also calisthenics athletes are among the strongest in relative strength. If a tall guy masters the same calisthenics skill like a small guy, what does that say about their relative strength?! Be reminded of the extra weight some people carry and what this means in order to fight gravity.\r\n\r\n<strong>Power (AKA Explosive Strength) </strong>\r\n\r\nPower considers how quickly you can use your strength. Distance over time plays a significant role in this one.\r\n\r\nFor conceptual purposes, think of an athlete propelling himself off of the ground or a football player exploding off the line. While each of these movements are markedly different from one another, both in form and speed of movement, they all require explosive strength.\r\n\r\nIn gymnastics or in calisthenics you can measure explosive strength by how fast one can move his body around or which distance one can create. If you look at the freestyle competitions of calisthenics you will see athletes that can move around quicker due to technique but also due to power. To be clear, the easiest way we can see how powerful we are is by how high or far we can jump. Another example comes from fighting sports, where power is measured by how hard you can punch and kick. If Bruce Lee or Conor MC Gregor kick or punch you from up close and your friend does the same from the same distance I am pretty sure you will know where we getting at.\r\n\r\nThe key to understand is this. If you are trying to deliver a great amount of force to your target, and may have a high level of strength, but if you are too slow (make distance over time), you\'ll lack power.\r\n\r\n<strong>Strength Endurance </strong>\r\n\r\nStrength Endurance is the ability to perform a near maximal level of strength repeatedly over a period of time. In simple terms this means the longer you can stay in an activity with minimal decrease in efficiency, the better your strength endurance.\r\n\r\nGymnasts performing ring strength skills one after another in a routine or calisthenics athletes in a freestyle session are great examples for that type of strength. The intensity and exercise chosen determines the toughness. Enjoy!\r\n\r\nLet’s hope this little excursion into the world of strength types has helped you to adjust your training. Remember, you can train for any skill and any goal very specifically - this is what we offer with our app. Learn, evolve, master – with us. Choose a skill, select your goals and get individualized workout plans designed by professionals. Change gears and hit the bars. <a href=\"http://www.ykings.com\">www.ykings.com</a>\r\n\r\nTeam Ykings\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','A quick guide about strength types','','publish','open','open','','a-quick-guide-about-strength','','','2016-07-08 06:45:38','2016-07-08 06:45:38','',0,'http://ykings.com/?p=1689',0,'post','',0),(1690,1,'2016-07-07 15:27:17','2016-07-07 15:27:17','','iStock_000084255861_Large','','inherit','open','closed','','istock_000084255861_large','','','2016-07-07 15:27:17','2016-07-07 15:27:17','',1689,'http://ykings.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/iStock_000084255861_Large.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1691,1,'2016-07-07 15:29:43','2016-07-07 15:29:43','After reading this article you will know\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li>why it makes sense to know about strength types</li>\r\n 	<li>how to measure and compare strength</li>\r\n 	<li>how you can align your training to strength</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nStrength can be split into several different forms, and to address the right type in accordance with your goals is what we are going to cover in this blog post. What you will do in strength training heavily depends on what kind of strength suits your needs.\r\n\r\nWe all have our own preferences and goals, and none of the types of strength described here is superior to the others. Generally we recommend prioritizing a specific strength type for a certain period of time. Grow through adversity and explore other worlds from time to time. To be clear, working on one does not mean you are excluding the others, just know which strength type you want to emphasize more than the others to make the most efficient progress towards the goals you have.\r\n\r\nSo what are these strength types, what do they mean and do you translate and integrate them in your training?\r\n\r\nWe cover four basic types of strength\r\n\r\n★ Absolute Strength\r\n\r\n★ Relative Strength\r\n\r\n★ Power (aka Explosive or Speed Strength)\r\n\r\n★ Strength Endurance\r\n\r\n<strong>Absolute Strength </strong>\r\n\r\nAbsolute Strength is the maximum force your musculature can exert for a particular action, whether it’s a press, a squat, or a pull.\r\n\r\nThe most renowned sport for absolute strength is powerlifting. Powerlifters train for absolute strength, everything they do is geared towards improving a 1 rep Max in three lifts -- the squat, bench press, and deadlift. In general, training for this involves lifting weights at 85%+ of the maximal weight you can lift for several sets of a few repetitions. So in that discipline there is a way to measure it in total weight lifted.\r\n\r\nHow about calisthenics? In calisthenics strength competitions you can’t measure that why, because don’t forget that participants need to carry their own weight as well. Here you will need either weight classes or consider the pound for pound type of strength which is what we will cover next.\r\n\r\n<strong>Relative Strength </strong>\r\n\r\nRelative strength concerns your maximum effort in relation to your bodyweight. I am pretty sure you heard the term pound for pound before, either in boxing or from recent UFC discussions lingering around Jon Jones (Light Heavyweight) and Demetrius Johnson (Featherweight). This “pound for pound” strength is often used to explain the strength in connection to the respective bodyweight and therefore considers but also favours people who are of lower bodyweight.\r\n\r\nGymnasts and for this matter also calisthenics athletes are among the strongest in relative strength. So, show some respect for the tall and big guys trying to master the static skills of our sport. If they can do what a smaller guy can do, what does that say about their relative strength?!\r\n\r\n<strong>Power (AKA Explosive Strength) </strong>\r\n\r\nPower considers how quickly you can use your strength. Distance plays a significant role in this one.\r\n\r\nThrowing a heavy ball a short distance is not as powerful as throwing a lighter ball twice as far. Lifting the same barbell weight but taking longer to do it indicates the lack of power. In case of doubt ask a physicist how to measure power. However, we don’t need to be this technical.\r\n\r\nIn gymnastics or in calisthenics you can measure explosive strength by how fast one can move his body around or which distance one can create. If you look at the freestyle competitions of calisthenics you will know what I mean. To be clearer, we can see how powerful we are by how high or far we can jump. Another example comes from fighting sports, where power is measured by how hard you can punch and kick. Ask Bruce Lee or Conor MC Gregor.\r\n\r\nThe key to understand is this. If you are trying to deliver a great amount of force to your target, and may have a high level of strength, but if you are too slow (make distance over time), you\'ll lack power.\r\n\r\n<strong>Strength Endurance </strong>\r\n\r\nStrength Endurance is the ability to perform a near maximal level of strength repeatedly over a period of time. In simple terms this means the longer you can stay in an activity with minimal decrease in efficiency, the better your strength endurance.\r\n\r\nGymnasts performing ring strength skills one after another in a routine or calisthenics athletes in a freestyle session are great examples for that type of strength. The intensity and exercise chosen determines the toughness. Enjoy!\r\n\r\nLet’s hope this little excursion into the world of strength types has helped you to adjust your training. Remember, you can train for any skill and any goal very specifically - this is what we offer with our app. Learn, evolve, master – with us. Choose a skill, select your goals and get individualized workout plans designed by professionals. Change gears and hit the bars. <a href=\"http://www.ykings.com\">www.ykings.com</a>\r\n\r\nTeam Ykings\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','A quick guide about strength','','inherit','closed','closed','','1689-revision-v1','','','2016-07-07 15:29:43','2016-07-07 15:29:43','',1689,'http://ykings.com/index.php/2016/07/07/1689-revi